A new course at Harvard University this year encourages students to sleep more, in an attempt to combat the growing "macho" culture that makes them submit to "all night" learning sessions, energized with a lot of caffeine.
A scientist has discovered that students of the most prestigious university in the world often do not master even the basic concepts of how they should take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the one who created the course, which is thought to be the first of its kind in the United States.
It was inspired to create the course after holding a conference on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning ability.
“In the end, a girl came and said to me, “Why am I being told this only now, in the last year?”
She told me that she had never been told about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, introduced for the first time this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance, as well as the general wellbeing.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were seriously deprived of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course may involve a number of interactive tasks.
Within a section is presented the image of a dorm room, and students can click on coffee mugs, curtains, gym pants and books to tell them what the effects of caffeine and light are and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deficiency, but also about the importance of a sleep program.
In another section, participants were told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily schedule.
"We know that we cannot change the behaviour of students instantly.
But we believe that they have a right to know, just as everyone has a right to know what the health effects of smoking are," added Professor Czeisler.
The culture that makes students proud to have learned all night still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students have turned sleep deprivation into a growing problem.
Sufficient sleep, of good quality, should be a student's "secret weapon" to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deprivation makes the brain think that the body is hungry, which makes the students feel that they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler create the course after attending one of his first years at Harvard.
He said that the course opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course for all students.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before enrolling in this institution where the competition is fierce.
Professor Czeisler has advised students to set up an alarm to know when it is time to go to bed, as well as for waking up time, and to know what are the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LEDs, which can disturb the circadian rhythm and cause difficulties when they try to fall asleep.
