HIV/AIDS: China reports 14% increase in new cases
China has announced a 14% increase in the number of Chinese citizens suffering from HIV and AIDS.
More than 820,000 people are affected by this disease in China, officials say.
About 40,000 new cases were reported only in the second quarter of 2018.
The vast majority of new cases have been sexually transmitted, unlike in the past.
In the past, HIV has spread rapidly to some areas of China as a result of transfusions of infected blood.
But the number of people who contracted HIV in this way has been reduced to almost zero, Chinese health officials say at a conference in Yunnan Province.
From year to year, however, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China increased by 100,000.
Sexual HIV transmission is an acute problem in the LGBT community in China.
Homosexuality was decriminalised in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is considered widespread.
Because of the country's conservative values, studies estimate that 70-90% of men who have sex with other men will eventually end up marrying a woman.
Many cases of transmission of diseases come from inadequate sexual protection measures in such relationships.
Since 2003, the government of China has promised universal access to anti-HIV drugs as part of an effort to solve the problem.
