The latest technology legend project, Inrupt, is a company based on Solid, Berners-Lee's open-source platform.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and who has the right to access the information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intention behind Inrupt was "global domination".
"Now we have to do it," he talked about starting up.
"It's a historic moment."
The app uses Solid technology to enable people to create their own "personal online data archives" or PODs.
It may contain contact lists, programs, calendars, musical libraries or other personal and professional tools.
It's as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify would all be available in one browser, all at once.
What is unique about this personal online data archive is that the user has complete control over who can access this type of information.
The company calls this "personal data consolidation".
According to the CEO of the company, John Bruce, the idea is for Inrupt to contribute adequate resources, processes and skills, so as to make Solid available to everyone.
Currently, the company is composed of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, a team of developers working on the project and a community of volunteer programmers.
From this week on, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralised applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team don't talk to "Facebook and Google about whether or not to introduce a complete change when their business models are completely screwed up all of a sudden.
"We don't ask their permission."
In a post published on Saturday on Medium, Berners-Lee wrote that "The Inrupt mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of a new Internet on Solid."
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he created the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate on Internet neutrality.
Even after launching Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I am incredibly optimistic for this next era of the Internet," Berners-Lee added.
Bernard Vann: The clergyman who won the Victoria Cross in World War I is celebrated
The only clergyman of the Church of England who won a Victorian Cross medal as a combatant in World War I was celebrated in his hometown after 100 years.
Lieutenant Colonel Bernard Vann won the medal on 29 September 1918 in the attack at Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
He was killed by a sniper four days later and never knew that he had received Britain's highest military honor.
A commemorative stone was unveiled Saturday by his two grandchildren during the Rushden parade in Northamptonshire.
One of the grandchildren, Michael Vann, said it was "wonderfully symbolic" that the stone would be unveiled exactly 100 years after his grandfather won the medal.
According to the London Gazette, on 29 September 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Vann led his battalion across the Canal of Saint-Quentin "through a very thick fog and under heavy artillery and machine guns fire.
Later, he rushed to the front line and, with "a fantastic bravery", opened the way for the soldiers, then attacked an artillery nest himself and managed to eliminate three of the detachment's weapons.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on 4 October 1918, just a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said that his grandfather's actions were "one thing I know I will never be able to equal, but that makes me feel humble".
He and his brother, Dr. James Vann, also placed a crown after the parade, which was led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Orchestra.
Michael Vann said that "he feels very honored to play a role in the parade" and added that "the value of a true hero is demonstrated by the support that a lot of people give him.
MMA fans stayed up all night to see Bellator 206, but they got Peppa Pig cartoons instead.
Imagine you stayed up all night watching Bellator 206, an event with many stars, just so you couldn't watch the main event.
The San Jose event program contained 13 fights, including six on the main panel, and was to be broadcast live all night in Britain on Channel 5.
At 6 a.m., just as Gegard Mousasi was preparing to face Rory MacDonald, British viewers were amazed when the broadcast was replaced by an episode of Peppa Pig.
Some were not satisfied at all because they stayed up all night to watch the fight.
A fan tweeted the move to the children's cartoon as "a kind of a bad joke".
"Governmental regulations say that this content is not suitable for 6 a.m., so they had to change to children's programs," said Dave Schwartz, senior vice president of Bellator for marketing and communication, when asked about the broadcast.
"Peppa pig, yes."
Scott Coker, president of Bellator, said that in the future they would schedule their events so that they could also be watched by British viewers.
"When I think about reruns, I think we could probably work it out," Coker said.
"But it's six in the morning on a Sunday here and we won't be able to do that until Sunday, our time, or Monday, their time.
But we're working on it.
Believe me, when the program changed, I started getting a lot of text messages and they weren't all friendly.
We tried to solve the situation, we thought it was a technical mix-up.
But it wasn't about that, it was about government regulation.
I can promise it won't happen next time.
We'll stick to five fights instead of six, as we usually do. We tried to give fans more and we crossed the line.
It's an unfortunate situation."
Desert Island Discs: Tom Daley felt "inferior" because of sexuality
Olympic diver Tom Daley says he grew up feeling inferior to everyone because of his sexuality, but this motivated him to succeed.
The 24-year-old athlete said he didn't realize until he got to school that "not everyone is like me".
Invited to the first show Desert Island Discs presented by Lauren Laverne on Radio 4, he said he talks about gay people's rights to give others "hope".
The athlete also said that when he became a parent, he cared less about the Olympics.
Kirsty Young, the regular presenter of the tradition show, will be absent for several months due to illness.
Invited in the first edition presented by Laverne, Daley said that when he was a child he felt "inferior" to others because "it was not socially acceptable to like both boys and girls."
He said, "So far, these feelings of inferiority and the fact that I felt different, were the real things that gave me strength and stamina to achieve success."
He wanted to prove that he was "someone," he said, so he wouldn't disappoint everyone when they finally found out about his sexuality.
The winner of two bronze medals at the Olympic Games became a renowned supporter of the LGBT campaigns and took advantage of the release at this year's Commonwealth Games in Australia to urge several countries to decriminise homosexuality.
He said that he decided to speak because he felt lucky that he could live freely, without consequences, and because he wanted to give others "hope".
The world's triple champion said that "he was taken by surprise" by falling in love with a man, American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black.
Daley married last year the Oscar-winning filmmaker, who is 20 years older than him, but said the age difference was never a problem.
"When you go through so much at such a young age" -- he participated in the first Olympics when he was only 14 years old, and his father died of cancer after three years -- he said, it's hard to find someone of the same age who's been through the same good and bad moments.
In June, they became the parents of a boy named Robert Ray Black-Daley, which, according to Daley, changed his whole perspective.
"If I had been asked last year, I would have been only interested in winning a gold medal," he said.
"You know what? There are more important things than gold medals at the Olympics.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie."
His son bears his father's name, Robert, who died in 2011, at the age of 40, after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said that his father did not accept that he was going to die and that one of the last things he wanted was to find out if they had received tickets for the London Olympics in 2012, because he wanted to be in the first place.
"I couldn't say 'you won't be able to be a father in the first place'," he said.
"I was holding his hand when he stopped breathing and it was only after he stopped breathing and died that I finally accepted that he was not invincible," he said.
The following year, Daley competed at the 2012 Olympics and won the bronze medal.
"I knew that's what I'd dreamed of my whole life, jumping in front of people in my country at the Olympics, there's no better feeling," he said.
This also inspired him in his chosen music, Proud by Heather Small, which encouraged him before the Olympic Games and still thrills him.
Desert Island Discs is broadcast on BBC Radio 4 on Sunday at 11:15.
Mickelson, out of shape, was put on the bench on Saturday in the Ryder Cup.
American Phil Mickelson will set a record on Saturday, when he will play in the forty-seventh Ryder Cup match, but he will have to recover in good shape so that this is not an unfortunate occasion.
Mickelson, who plays in the biennial event for the 12th time, another record, was placed on Captain Jim Furyk's bench for the fourballs and foursome on Saturday.
Instead of being at the center of the action, as it has often been for the United States team, the quintuple major tournament winner divided his day between being a cheerleading teammate and practicing his kicks, hoping that he would right what he did wrong.
The 48-year-old player has never had the straightest drives, not even at the best time of his career, so he is not the best choice for the narrow terrain at Le Golf National, where long areas of rough often punish unfair blows.
And if the field is not a big enough challenge, in Sunday's ninth game Mickelson will face Francesco Molinari, the meticulous British Open champion, who has allied himself with Tommy Fleetwood and won all four matches of the week.
Mickelson's match could prove absolutely crucial for the Americans, led by four points at the entry into the 12 simple matches, which must begin in force at this stage.
Furyk declared himself confident in his player's ability, but could not have said otherwise anyway.
"He fully understood the role he played today, patted me on the shoulder, hugged me and told me he would be ready for tomorrow," Furyk said.
"He has a lot of confidence in himself.
He is a member of the Hall of Fame and has contributed a great deal to these teams in the past and this week.
I probably never imagined he'd be in two games.
I imagined more, but that's what happened, and that's how I thought we had to do it.
He wants to play, like everyone else."
On Sunday, Mickelson will break Nick Faldo's record for most of the games played in the Ryder Cup.
This could be the end of his career in the Ryder Cup, which has never stood up to his personal record.
Mickelson has 18 matches won, 20 lost and seven halves, although Furyk said his presence brought some intangible advantages to the team.
"He's funny, he's sarcastic, he's smart, he likes to joke with players, he's a great guy in the team locker room," he explained.
“I think young players have fun joking with him, it was fun to see them do it during the week.
His role is more important, it's not just about the game."
Europe team captain Thomas Bjorn knows that the considerable advance may soon disappear
Thomas Bjorn, the captain of Europeans, knows from experience that the considerable advance held before the first day of simple challenges in the Ryder Cup can easily turn into an uncomfortable journey.
