Germany's new warship, delayed again
The latest frigate of German naval forces should have been put into operation in 2014 to replace the old Cold War warships, but this will not happen until next year, due to faulty systems and rising costs, local media reported.
The entry into service of the ship "Rheinland-Pfalz", the standard ship of the new Baden-Wuerttemberg frigate class, was now delayed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, which quotes a military spokesman.
The vessel was supposed to be introduced into the maritime forces in 2014, but post-delivery problems affected this ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships the Navy ordered in 2007 will replace the old Bremen-class frigates.
It is assumed that they will be equipped with a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as stealth technologies, which provide a low radar, infrared and acoustic footprint.
Other important features will include longer maintenance periods; it should be possible for the new frigates to go on missions lasting two years without returning to the original port.
However, continuing delays mean that these state-of-the-art warships, which are said to increase Germany's maritime strength, will already be obsolete before entering the service, notes Die Zeit.
The unfortunate frigate F125 was discussed in the press last year when the German Navy officially refused to take over the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy returned a ship to the builder after delivery.
Not much information is available about the reasons for refusal, but the German media cited a number of crucial "software and hardware failures" that would have made the warship useless on a combat mission.
Software failures were particularly important because the Baden-Wuerttemberg class ships will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, only half of the crews on the older frigates of the Bremen class.
In addition, it has been shown that the vessel was too heavy, which reduced its performance and limited the Navy's ability to add future facilities.
It is believed that the 7,000-ton "Rheinland-Pfalz" is twice as heavy as the German ships used in World War II.
In addition to faulty mechanisms, and the price of the entire project, including crew training, has become a cause for concern.
It is said to have reached an amazing 3.1 billion euros (3.6 billion dollars) from the initial price of 2.2 billion euros.
The problems of the newest frigates are of particular importance given the latest warnings that Germany's maritime power is falling.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the defence commission in Germany's parliament, acknowledged that the Navy "has begun to run out of ships that can be sent on missions".
The official said the problem has grown steadily over time, as old vessels have been decommissioned without being replaced by new ones.
He deplored that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class frigates had entered into operation within the Navy.
National Trust spies on bats' secret lives
New research that is being conducted on a Scottish Highland property wants to reveal how bats use their environment to hunt their prey.
It is hoped that the discoveries will reveal new things about the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help future conservation activities.
The study conducted by scientists of the National Trust for Scotland will analyse common dwarf bats and Pygmies bats, as well as eared bats and water bats from Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be located in key places around the property to track bat activity throughout the season.
The NHS team and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using manual detectors.
The specialized audio analysis of all records will estimate the frequency of bat sounds and what species emit certain sounds.
A map of the habitat and a report will also be produced to create a detailed, scale picture of their behaviour in the environment.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation consultant for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as lawn creation, and which is the best way to maintain forest meadows for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across Britain have declined considerably in the last century.
They are at risk from construction and development work affecting their nests, but also from habitat loss.
Wind turbines and public lighting are also risks, as are fly traps and some chemical treatments for construction materials, as well as attacks on domestic cats.
Actually, bats aren't blind.
However, because they hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated ecolocation technique to accurately identify insects and obstacles on their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major parks and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, is seriously thinking about bats.
They have ten trained experts, who regularly conduct studies, control nests and sometimes carry out rescue missions.
The organization even created the first and only reserve of bats in Scotland, on the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight out of ten species of bats are found in Scotland.
The owner of the estate, David Thompson, says this is the ideal territory for bats.
"Here, at Thorave, the area is wonderful for bats," he says.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and a perfect habitat.
But there are many things we don't know about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us understand what they need to multiply."
It underlines the importance of looking for bats before performing maintenance work on properties, because the mere unintentional destruction of a maternal nest could kill up to 400 females and puppies, which could destroy the entire local population.
Bats are protected, and killing, harassing or disturbing them, as well as destroying their nests, are forbidden actions.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official at the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help them.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about bats and we don't know how populations evolve for many of our species."
