Brexit: Britain "would regret forever" loss of car manufacturers
Britain "would regret forever" if it lost its status as world leader in car production after Brexit, said Business Secretary Greg Clark.
He added that it was "disquieting" that Toyota UK told the BBC that if Britain exits the EU without an agreement, it would temporarily stop production at its factory in Burnaston, near Derby.
"We need an agreement," Clark said.
The Japanese car manufacturer said the impact of delays at the border in a Brexit without agreement could cost jobs.
The factory in Burnaston, where the Auris and Aventis brands of Toyota are made, produced nearly 150,000 cars last year, of which 90% were exported to the rest of the European Union.
"My opinion is that if Britain leaves the EU by the end of March, production will stop in our factory," said Marvin Cooke, Toyota's CEO at Burnaston.
Other UK car manufacturers, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover, said they fear leaving the EU without an agreement on cross-border trade.
BMW, for example, says that after Brexit, it will close the Oxford factory where the Mini model is produced for a month.
The main concerns are caused by what producers call supply chain risks in the case of a Brexit without agreement.
Toyota's production line operates on the "fixed on time" principle: for custom-made machines, parts arrive every 37 minutes from suppliers in the UK and in the EU.
If Britain leaves the EU without an agreement on 29 March, problems could arise at the border, which, according to industrial producers, could cause delays and a shortage of parts.
It would be impossible for Toyota to store more inventory for one day at its factory in Derbyshire, the company says, so the production would be stopped.
Clark said Theresa May's Chequers plan for future relations with the EU is "precisely calibrated to avoid these delays at the border".
"There must be an agreement. We want to have the best agreement, which will allow us not only to enjoy the success of the present, but also to take advantage of this opportunity," he told BBC Radio 4 Today.
"The evidence not only from Toyota, but also from other producers shows that we must be able to continue to use what was a very successful supply chain set."
Toyota could not specify how long production will have to be stopped, but warned that increased prices could reduce the long-term competitive capacity of the plant and ultimately lead to job losses.
Peter Tsouvallaris, who has been working at Burnaston for 24 years and is in charge of the United Union at the factory, said members are increasingly concerned: "The experience has taught me that after they disappear, these jobs do not return."
A government spokesman said: "We have created a precise and credible plan for our future relationship with the EU."
Trump's meeting with Rosenstein could be postponed again, says the White House
Donald Trump's high-level meeting with Deputy Prosecutor General Rod Rosenstein could be "delayed another week", as he fights for Supreme Court nominee Brett Kavanaugh, continues, the White House said Sunday.
Rosenstein oversees Special Advisor Robert Mueller, who investigates Russia's interference in elections, links between Trump's aids and Russia, and the president's potential obstruction of justice.
Rumors of Trump firing the deputy state's attorney, thus jeopardising Mueller's independence, have been circulating in circles in Washington for months.
Earlier this month, The New York Times reported that Rosenstein discussed the possibility of wearing a microphone to record conversations with Trump and the possibility of suspending the president through Amendment 25 to the US Constitution.
Rosenstein denied this report.
But last Monday he went to the White House, and reports say he was about to resign.
Instead, a meeting with Trump, who was at the time at the United Nations headquarters in New York, was announced for Thursday.
Trump said he "would rather not" fire Rosenstein, but then the meeting was postponed to avoid a conflict with the Senate Legal Commission hearing, in which Kavanaugh and one of the women who accused him of sexual misconduct, Dr. Christine Blasey Ford, testified.
On Friday, Trump called for a week-long FBI investigation into charges against Kavanaugh, which again postponed the vote in the Senate plenary.
Trump's press secretary, Sarah Sanders, showed up on Fox News on Sunday.
Asked about the meeting with Rosenstein, she said: “A date has not been set yet. It can be this week or it can be postponed for a week, taking into account all the other things that are now happening at the Supreme Court.
But we'll see, and I always like to keep the press informed."
Some reporters would dispute this claim: Sanders has not had a press briefing at the White House since September 10.
Host Chris Wallace asked why.
Sanders said that the reduction in briefings was not caused by the dislike of TV reporters, who like to show off, although he added: "I don't deny that they like to show off."
Then he suggested that direct contact between Trump and the press would be enhanced.
"The president is attending more questions and answers than all previous presidents," she said, adding without mentioning any evidence: "I have analyzed the figures."
"There will still be briefings," Sanders said, but "it seems much better for the press to have the opportunity to address the questions directly to the President of the United States, not to me.
We try to do this most of the time and you can see that we have done this many times in the last few weeks, and discussions with the President of the United States will replace press briefings when it is available."
Trump usually answers questions when leaving the White House or attending open sessions or press conferences with visiting dignitaries.
Press conferences given exclusively by him are rare.
This week in New York, the president demonstrated why this is happening, with an impromptu appearance, somewhere bizarre, in front of reporters gathered.
A State Secretary of the Ministry of Health is addressed in a letter to EU employees at the National Health Service (NHS) in Scotland about concerns about Brexit
The Secretary of State wrote to EU employees working at the NHS branch in Scotland to express their gratitude on behalf of the country and the desire for them to remain after Brexit.
