Foreign buyers will be charged a higher fee for the purchase of property in the United Kingdom
Foreign buyers will pay a higher stamp tax when buying a property in the United Kingdom, and the additional money will be used to help homeless people, according to the new Conservative Party plans
This change will neutralise Corbyn's efforts to attract young people with voting rights
Judicial stamp duty to be applied to non-taxpayers in the United Kingdom
Treasury expects to raise up to £120 million a year to help homeless people
Foreign buyers will be charged a higher rate of judicial stamp duty when buying a property in the United Kingdom, and additional money will be used to help homeless people, as Theresa May is expected to announce today.
The change will be seen as an attempt to neutralise the success of Jeremy Corbyn's efforts to attract young people with voting rights, promising better-priced homes and targeting high-income earners.
The higher stamp fee will be applied to natural and legal persons who are not taxable in the United Kingdom, and the additional money thus obtained will be used to support the Government's efforts to help homeless people.
The surcharge, which is added to the current stamp fee, including the high levels two years ago for the second property and the properties purchased for rental purposes, could reach a value of 3%.
The Treasury expects this change to add up to 120 million pounds a year.
About 13% of the newly built properties in London are purchased by non-residents in the UK, which leads to higher prices and puts those who want to buy their first home in difficulty.
Several prosperous areas in the country, especially in the capital, have become "ghost cities" due to the large number of foreign buyers who spend much of their time outside the country.
The new policy comes only weeks after Boris Johnson asked for a reduction in the stamp fee to help young people buy their first home.
He accused large construction firms of keeping property prices high as a result of purchasing land without using it, and asked Theresa May to waive taxes on affordable houses in order to address the UK's "house problem".
Corbyn announced a series of proposals for attractive real estate reforms, including rent controls and an end to unmotivated discharges.
It also wants to give councils greater powers in building new homes.
Theresa May said: “Last year I said I would dedicate my prime ministership to fulfilling the British dream, a better life for every new generation.
And that means remedying the problems that exist in the real estate market.
Britain will always be open to people who want to live, work and build a life here.
However, it is not fair that people who do not live in the UK, as well as companies with headquarters abroad, can buy homes as easily as British residents who work hard.
For too many people, the dream of owning a house has become far too distant, and living in undignified conditions is far too real."
Jack Ross: "My ultimate goal is to be the manager of the Scotland national team."
Jack Ross, the manager of the Sunderland football team, said that his "final goal" is to eventually become the manager of the Scottish national team.
The 42-year-old Scottish enjoys the challenge of "resurrecting" the northeast club, which currently ranks 3rd in the First League, with a difference of three points from the first place.
