How can the trade war between the United States and China be beneficial for Beijing?
The salves that announced the start of the trade war between the United States and China were deafening and, although it seems to be a long way to go until its end, fighting between the two countries could be beneficial for Beijing in the long term, experts say.
Donald Trump, President of the United States, issued his first warning earlier this year by imposing duties on key Chinese imports, including solar, steel and aluminium panels.
The most important escalation occurred this week with new taxes, which affected products worth $200 billion (150 billion pounds), effectively applying taxes on half of all goods in China that reach US territory.
Beijing has been avenged every time, most recently imposing a tax of between 5 and 10% on US products worth $60 billion.
China has warned that it will respond to every blow by the United States and it is unlikely that the world's second largest economy will take a step back in the near future.
For Washington to withdraw, China must agree to its demands, but publicly ceding to the United States would be far too humiliating for Xi Jinping, the president of China.
However, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards well, US commercial war pressures could positively support China in the long term, reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
"The fact that a quick political decision taken in Washington or Beijing could lead to an economic collapse in both countries would in fact be more dangerous than what has been expected so far," said Abigail Grace, an associate researcher focusing on Asia at the Centre for New American Security, a group of experts.
Syria ready for refugee return, Foreign Minister says
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and is seeking help in rebuilding the country devastated by a war that has lasted for more than seven years.
During his speech at the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said the situation in the country is improving.
"Today, the conditions on the ground are more stable and secure, thanks to the progress made in fighting terrorism," he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate areas destroyed by terrorists so that things can get back to normal.
Existing conditions allow refugees to return voluntarily to the country they were forced to leave due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at daily life and living.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the war broke out in 2011.
Six million people who continue to live in the country need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would be happy to receive help rebuilding the devastated country.
But he stressed that conditional assistance or aid from countries sponsored by the insurgency would not be accepted.
