News on the red tide: concentrations decreased in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Wildlife Protection Commission shows a general decrease in red tide concentrations for certain areas of the Tampa Gulf.
According to the Commission, uneven inflorescence conditions are reported in areas in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier – suggesting lower concentrations.
This inflorescence of the red tide extends to an area of the coast of about 210 km, from the north of Pinellas County to the south of Lee County.
The spots can be found about 16 km off Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Average concentrations found in or off Pinellas County were reported last week, as well as low to high concentrations in Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations in Sarasota County or off-limits, background to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, background to high concentrations in Lee County and off-shore, and low concentrations in Collier County.
Respiratory irritations continue to be reported in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No cases of respiratory irritation have been reported in the northwest of the American state of Florida in the last week.
